\section{Introduction}
\label{introduction}

Because of the finite fossil fuel sources and the impracticality of replacing liquid chemical fuels for alternatives such as batteries, especially for the aviation sector, technologies for the production of synthetic liquid fuels are required. However far the exhaustion of fossil fuel sources is, it is prudent to have such alternatives ready to deploy. For this reason governments and the scientific community have been trying to solve this question for the past two decades at least.

The aviation sector is particularly dependent on liquid hydrocarbons. Aircraft are built to last many decades, so that there will be a need for drop-in fuels, that is, fuels that can be used in current aircraft without any need for modifications. Another reason is that aircraft must be light, ruling out current battery technology.

The production of synthetic fuels only makes sense in mixed or fully renewable grid \cite{barke_are_2022}. The conversion of biomass --- sources of carbon --- to liquid fuels such as sustainable aviation fuel (SAF), is an energy intensive process, thus the reason to operate in a petroleum free manner, otherwise carbon accumulation in the atmosphere would be greater for SAF plus fossil energy than in a pure fossil energy sector. Another concern is with the availability of green hydrogen for some processes such as hydrodeoxygenation of oils and fatty acids \cite{alonso_catalytic_2010} as most of current hydrogen is supplied from natural gas reforming. In this way \ce{H2} producing SAF routes can be merged with \ce{H2} consuming ones to reduce environmental impacts \cite{alonso_catalytic_2010}.

The most mentioned SAF production processes are: (1) biomass biodigestion to produce biogas (\ce{CO2 + CH4}), which is reformed to syn-gas; or biomass direct gasification (partial combustion) to syn-gas, that is then fed to a Fischer-Tropsch Synthesis reactor (FTS) to produce aliphatic and branched hydrocarbons; (2) alcohol-to-jet (ATJ) is another promising technology, it takes alcohols and puts them through a oligomerization process to produce hydrocarbons \cite{wang_bio-jet_2016}. The advantage of ATJ is that it can mobilize the already developed ethanol production plants, which have successfully operated for many decades in countries such as Brazil; (3) the third main route for hydrocarbon production from biomass is the hydroprocessing of esters and fatty acids (HEFA), which takes animal fats and vegetable oils and puts them through high temperature and hydrogen pressure to dehydrate and hydrogenate the oils into a deoxygenated mixture similar in nature to crude oil.

In this context this paper aims to provide thorough bibliometric analysis of the available literature so researchers can orient themselves. To avoid already explored paths and perhaps hint at promising ones. Such analysis is also useful for those ones desiring to conduct a literature review: a statistical analysis of the bibliometric space can point researchers in the direction of fundamental literature that is not always evident in a superficial unoriented search. A literature review based on bibliometric analysis is also less likely to be biased by an author's personal preference because of its statistical nature. Nevertheless, one must try to avoid inserting bias into the research question, this is why this paper is founded on a very generic search query. Even with this precaution, during the analysis the chosen search term --- sustainable aviation fuel --- presented itself as not always true to its sustainable nature. It is a common term used in the literature that sometimes is used to refer to synthetic aviation fuel sourced from non-fossil carbon. The problem with this is that even if the feedstock is non-fossil, the resulting product might not be sustainable. Perhaps a more appropriate term for the cases when authors can not guarantee sustainability would be "alternative aviation fuel". One such approach to assess sustainability is life cycle assessment. Still, the "sustainable aviation fuel" query was kept even if the term is sometimes incorrectly used, as the focus of this analysis is on truly sustainable aviation fuels.

\section{Methods}
\label{methods}

This paper was written using a systematic methodology published by Aria and Cuccurullo \cite{aria_bibliometrix_2017} based on the R programming language. A versatile tool that can provide way beyond statistical calculations, it is a full fledged computer language that can even generate automatic reports, such as this paper, written using the R 'knitr' package in conjunction with \LaTeX. All code used here was licensed under GPL. One hopes it to be helpful in future research.

\subsection{Data collection and research query}
\label{method_data_collection}

The complete dataset regarding Sustainable Aviation Fuels were collected from the Web of Science platform using the query “sustainable aviation fuel OR aviation biofuel OR aviation bio fuel OR bio-jet fuel OR bio jet fuel OR bio-aviation fuel OR bio aviation fuel (Topic)”. No time span restriction was set; this was done to get the whole historical timeline of this field.

Most of the results were generated using R, in particular the package 'bibliometrix' by Aria and Cuccurullo \cite{aria_bibliometrix_2017}.

\subsection{Author name disambiguation}
\label{method_AND}

In order to have a more accurate author count as well as better collaboration networks, it is necessary to perform author name disambiguation, in other words, to identify authors that written their names in different ways (synonyms) and different authors with the same name (homonyms). The R package “refsplitr” by ref. \cite{fournier_refsplitr_2020} was used for this purpose via \href{https://github.com/rafaelbeloduarte/SAF_bib_analysis_bibliometrix_R/blob/17412aa7544b8d78e61c24d38f667f9de1db4323/AND.R}{Script 1}. It automatically disambiguates names and puts the ones it can not resolve into a list for manual review. This was done by looking at authors' affiliations, coauthors, Orcid IDs and e-mail addressees. The list of authors synonyms and homonyms was fed into \href{https://github.com/rafaelbeloduarte/SAF_bib_analysis_bibliometrix_R/blob/17412aa7544b8d78e61c24d38f667f9de1db4323/recreate_ANDED_DB.py}{Script 2}, written in python to replace the names on the WOS dataset.

