Still in the red cluster there is a link between \textbf{efficiency}, \textbf{energy} and \textbf{exergy}. Exergy is the maximum amount of useful work that can be extracted from a system when it is brought to thermodynamic equilibrium. In contrast to energy it is not a conservative property. Essentially, exergy is a property that accounts for entropy and allows for the evaluation of system efficiency \cite{bejan_fundamentals_2002}. Exergy analysis can be applied both to SAF production \cite{hao_energy_2021} and aircraft engine performance \cite{balli_turbofan_2021, balli_thermodynamic_2021}.

The green cluster in  \autoref{fig:authors_keyword_network} refers to the core SAF technologies: \textbf{Fischer-Tropsch Synthesis} (FTS), \textbf{Alcohol-to-Jet} (ATJ) and \textbf{deoxygenation} of vegetable oils, which occurs primarily via \textbf{decarboxylation} reaction, commonly referred as DCO2. The deoxygenation of vegetable oils is often done by \textbf{hydroprocessing} of the esters and fatty acids in these oils (HEFA). Most of the biomass \textbf{feedstocks} cannot be used in its raw form in these processes, FTS requires the \textbf{gasification} of materials such as \textbf{lignocellulosic biomass} into syn-gas; ATJ is mostly fed by ethanol produced by fermentation; and deoxygenation uses oils extracted from plants. In contrast is \textbf{pyrolysis} in the blue cluster. Its main advantage is that feedstocks can be introduced into the plant without much treatment, on the other hand pyrolysis reactor product has lower quality and consequently greater refining cost. To make the reader familiar with the terms that emerged in \autoref{fig:authors_keyword_network} an overview of the most relevant SAF production technologies is given below. For more in-depth information, the three most cited reviews on the matter in the data set are a good start \cite{alonso_catalytic_2010, zhang_catalytic_2016, sims_overview_2010}.

\subsubsection{Overview of SAF technologies}
\label{SAF_overview}

\paragraph{Feedstocks and common characteristics}
\label{SAF_common}

SAF production takes on either starchy (including sugars), triglyceride
or lignocellulosic feedstocks into biorefineries, similar in nature to petroleum refineries, where the oxygen content is reduced and carbon chains of a wide range are formed, not always in this order, to produce a crude bio-oil that can be refined into various fractions \cite{alonso_catalytic_2010}. It is common the classification of biomass into first generation, sourced from food crops, and second generation, the non-food feedstocks, mostly lignocellulosic \cite{sims_overview_2010}. The fuels produced are usually parafinnic, with low sulfur and aromatics content. Lack of aromatics causes fuel seals to shrink \cite{yakovlieva_experimental_2023}, so at least 8 vol\% aromatics are required on jet fuels \cite{starck_production_2016}. Consequently SAF must be put through dehydrocyclization to increase aromatic concentration. Even if it is aromatized, current regulations require SAF to be blended up to 50\% with conventional jet fuel to ensure proper fuel quality \cite{enright_d7566_2023}.

\paragraph{Hydroprocessing of esters and fatty acids (HEFA)}
\label{HEFA}

Reacts esters and fatty acids with hydrogen to produce hydrocarbons \cite{monteiro_production_2022}. These reactions include deoxygenation, which increases the energy content; cracking, to break apart excessively long molecules, and isomerization, which reorganizes the carbon chains improving physical characteristics such as cold flow properties \cite{starck_production_2016}, particularly important for aircraft operated at the low temperatures found at high altitudes.

Currently, it is the largest industrial source of bio-oil, predominantly bio diesel. Fuels obtained by this route have a low sulfur content and generate less soot than fossil counterparts, but the selectivity to aviation kerosene is low because vegetable oils have carbon chains similar in length to what is encountered in diesel fuel \cite{doliente_bio-aviation_2020}.

\paragraph{Fischer-Tropsch synthesis (FTS)}
\label{fts}

It is a process for producing hydrocarbons from synthesis gas, a mixture of \ce{CO} and \ce{H2}, on catalysts based on cobalt, iron and/or ruthenium \cite{huber_synthesis_2006}. Synthesis gas can be sourced from lignocellulosic biomass via partial combustion (gasification) \cite{alonso_catalytic_2010} or from reforming of biogas (\ce{CH4} + \ce{CO2}) produced by anaerobic digestion of biomass. Compared to HEFA, FTS is less limited in terms of feedstock and emits less greenhouse gases, however it has a higher capital cost \cite{tiwari_environmental_2023}.

\paragraph{Alcohol-to-jet (ATJ)}
\label{atj}

ATJ is a technology of alcohol oligomerization, that is, short alcohol molecules --- monomers --- grow into long hydrocarbon compounds. The alcohols are dehydrated, oligomerized to long chain olefins and then hydrogenated into a mixture of alkanes. Due to the dehydration step, the catalysts used for ATJ are highly acidic aluminas and zeolites \cite{wang_bio-jet_2016}.

\paragraph{Pyrolysis and hydrothermal liquefaction (HTL)}
\label{pyrolysis_and_HTL}

The biomass, often cellulosic, is thermally decomposed into bio-char, biogas and bio-oil. The bio-oil is upgraded by hydrotreatment \cite{wang_bio-jet_2016} in a manner similar to what is done for HEFA, namely isomerization, cracking and deoxygenation. Along with gasification plus FTS, pyrolysis and HTL processes can make use of the most highly available and cheap source of renewable carbon: lignocellulosic biomass, while HEFA and ATJ can only resort to more noble feedstocks. Pyrolysis and HTL differ in process conditions. While pyrolysis is done under atmospheric pressure with dry biomass in the range of \num{400} \unit{\celsius} to \num{600} \unit{\celsius} and a residence time of a few seconds; hydrothermal liquefaction is a high pressure (7-20 \unit{\mega \pascal}) process performed in the range of \num{280} \unit{\celsius} to \num{380} \unit{\celsius} in the presence of water. HTL biocrude has lower oxygen content, higher energy value and lower upgrading cost than pyrolysis oil \cite{tzanetis_analysis_2017}.

