\paragraph{2010}
\label{2010}

A paper by Shonnard, Williams and Kalnes \cite{shonnard_camelina-derived_2010} (58 LC\footnote{Local Citations: citations mentioned in the papers of the dataset. As oposed to global citations, which are all the citations the paper ever received.}) on camelina derived jet-fuel and diesel via hydrotreatment (HEFA) presents a life cycle analysis of fuels from camelina cultivated on marginal lands and on lands used for food crops in the periods between harvests. Camelina is a weed native to Europe and well adapted to temperate climates with a short season crop. This route can have green house gas savings of up to 80\%. The biggest contributions to emissions are from feedstock production transportation and processing. During cultivation emissions are from farm equipment run on fossil diesel and \ce{NO2} from fertilizer. Hydroprocessing requires large amounts of hydrogen sourced from steam reforming of natural gas and transportation of feedstock in large volumes and distances is also a problem.

On the topic of climate science, Lee et al. \cite{lee_transport_2010} (42 LC) assess that the impact of aviation on the atmosphere and climate is on the direction of warming caused by \ce{CO2}, soot, water and \ce{NOx}.

Rye, Blakey and Wilson \cite{rye_sustainability_2010} (42 LC) present in a review a perspective not only from the point of view of sustainability but also from supply security. Even if a fuel is not sustainable it might still be valuable if it can replace current jet fuel in an oil shortage scenario. Secondary impacts such as those from land usage and coal or natural gas feedstocks to supplement production must be included in the emissions assessment. The two processes evaluated in the review are Fischer-Tropsch and hydroprocessing. Fischer-Tropsch is more suitable for supply diversification, because the source of the syn-gas does not matter from the production point of view. Hydroprocessing tends to less emissions when operated with sustainable feedstock.

\paragraph{2011}
\label{2011}

Another review by Blakey, Rye and Wilson \cite{blakey_aviation_2011} from the University of Sheffield in the UK, now on "Aviation gas turbine alternative fuels" is the most cited of the historical references with 111 local citations. It gives a thorough evaluation of what the authors call aviation alternative fuels. The choice of words is wise, using a term such as sustainable aviation fuels may not always be appropriate. Although alternative aviation fuels combustion is demonstrably cleaner than conventional jet fuel in almost every case --- from HEFA, FTS and ATJ fuels; the whole life cycle of land usage for feedstock production, fuel processing and transportation must be evaluated.  It is not yet known if all the proposed alternatives are indeed sustainable. Clearing of natural \ce{CO2} fixing land for fuel production, such as jungles and forests, could have the same if not worse environmental impact than fossil kerosene. Natural forested land has not only a direct impact on \ce{CO2} balance, but also on other factors such as rain cycles \cite{pielke_overview_2007} and the availability of land for every other form of life with which we share the planet and may depend on for our survival, even if is hard to quantify their relationship to mankind. These effects are sometimes referred in the literature as land use change impact, or LUC. In conclusion, as stated by Blakey, Rye and Wilson \cite{blakey_aviation_2011}: "alternative fuels should only be sourced from marginal land" and, one adds, from industrial and agricultural biomass residues.

Notice that fatty acid methyl esters (FAME) is seldom mentioned as a possibility for aviation. Their feedstocks have inappropriate chain lenghts as mentioned above, but also trace amounts of metals are carried from the feedstock to the final product, which is not permitted by current regulations due to negative effects on engines \cite{blakey_aviation_2011}. Although FAME and HEFA fuels are often sourced from the same feedstocks, they are not the same. FAME is produced by transesterification of fatty acids from vegetable oils with alcohols using a base as a catalyst. HEFA fuels are hydroprocessed vegetable oils, that is, they are reacted with hydrogen in the presence of a catalyst, which removes heteroatoms such as sulfur, nitrogen, oxygen and metals via hydrogenation and hydrogenolysis. More detailed information about hydroprocessing is presented by refs. \cite{ancheyta_hydroprocessing_2005, sonthalia_hydroprocessed_2019}.

A life cycle assessment by Agustinata et al. \cite{agusdinata_life_2011} (60 LC) for the production of biojet fuel in the United States concluded, at the time of publication, that the rate of adoption would not be sufficient to meet the emissions target.

In tandem with life cycle assessments there is another essential line of work on the properties of alternative aviation fuels (AJF). Industrial and pilot scale alternative jet fuels produced from fossil and bio-sourced carbon produced by Sasol, Shell, Rentech, UOP, and Syntroleum
Corporation were studied by Corporan et al. \cite{corporan_chemical_2011} (52 LC). AJFs heve better combustion than conventional JP-8 fuel --- less soot and \ce{CO}. But need to improve on three essential areas: 

{\enumerate{
  \item Lubricity\footnote{The capability of a compound to reduce friction and wear.} is poor due to the parafinic nature of the fuels and the hydrotreament to remove heteroatoms. Lubricity is improved in fuels that contain heteroatoms that increase polarity like oxygen, nitrogen and sulfur, as well as by the presence of double bonds \cite{knothe_lubricity_2005};
  \item The low aromatics content cause insufficient seal swell. In the short term aromatics from petroleum can be added. For the long term fuel seals can be substituted by materials that perform better with ATJs, like nitrile O-rings instead of elastomer \cite{corporan_chemical_2011};
  \item Density and volumetric energy content need to improve.

}}

\paragraph{2009}
\label{2009}

One of the major concerns of SAF researchers is on fuel emissions. For this reasons among the historicall references are papers on the impact of the aviation sector on climate change \cite{lee_aviation_2009, lee_transport_2010}.

\paragraph{2008}
\label{2008}

Searchinger et al. \cite{searchinger_use_2008} warned about thinking that a fuel is sustainable because its feedstock captures atmospheric carbon. When biofuel prices increase farmers clear land to increase crop production, which increases emissions. Crops like corn for ethanol production can double emissions, so great care must be put into the choice of feedstock.

\paragraph{2007}
\label{2007} The utilization of oil refineries for biofuel production was being considered \cite{huber_synergies_2007, huber_processing_2007}. The feedstock that would require minimal modifications for refinery conversion is vegetable oil. The problems for the production of aviation biofuels are the same mentioned above, supply scarceness, food security and yield. For lignocellulosic biomass, pyrolysis or hydrolysis are two options to produce bio-oil for hydrotreatment. It is available in greater quantities but the crude bio-oil is often of poor quality, which increases refining costs.

\section{The future}
\label{future}

A timeline of recent author's keywords and their time span, in \autoref{fig:trends}, gives hints to what is expected of SAF research in the coming years. Work on lignocellulosic biomass continues, it is the most difficult to process feedstock but has the greatest potential in terms of volume of production. HEFA, FTS, pyrolysis and HTL have been established as the core technologies for now. But there are great challenges ahead, proofs of concept are plentiful but not yet efficient enough for large scale production, and there are doubts on the availability of land to produce all the carbon necessary to meet current CORSIA goals. It is estimated that to provide the commercial aviation sector with a 50/50 blend of SAF \footnote{sourced from Jatropa oil} to conventional jet fuel would require 6\% of the world's arable land, just to meet the demands of a sector responsible for 2.6\% of \ce{CO2} emissions \cite{rye_sustainability_2010}, an unfeasible approach. Thus the upstream processes need to improve, the example of land usage given above is based on Jatropa oil alone, but there is more carbon in lignocellulosic biomass, its supply potential is more than four times larger than oil producing feedstock \cite{agusdinata_life_2011}. Efficiency improvements could involve hybrid processes, combining the strengths and weaknesses of these technologies. Surplus hydrogen from Firscher-Tropsch synthesis could be directed to hydroprocessing; the high diesel cut from the vegetable oils can be fueled into the transportation of lignocellulosic biomass; sugar cane bagasse from ethanol used in alcohol-to-jet can be gasified for FTS. As a matter of fact the future biorefinery should be as versatile as possible and capable to integrate all above mentioned technologies to increase efficiency. Indeed there are initiatives in Brazil at the moment for the implementation of pilot scale plants to utilize the ethanol industry residues to produce SAF, the data obtained will be a next step in the direction of energy security and emission reduction, besides the quality of life improvements around airports burning cleaner fuels.

